ke and Pine\nG.O.P. ECONOMY\nLincoln Banquet Speaker\nTells of Reductions\nEconomy of the present rvpu?'llr:\\u\u201c\nadministration, reduction of the \\mrl\ndebt, the proposed plan for the redue: I\ntion of taxation, the passage of the\nFordney-MeCumber tariff bill and\nthe return of prosperity during the\nrepublican administration, were the\nsalient pointe of the address of For.\nmer Gov. Laeslie M. Shaw, of lowa,\nbefore the #ind annual Lincoln's\nbirthday hanquet of the Young Men's\nRepublican club at the Crystal I'ool\nMonday night,\nGov. Bhaw's toplo was \"\"The Quad.\nrennial Search for an Issue,\u201d and hlll\nspeoech was partisan thruout,\nThe speaker opened his address\nwith a series of remarks about the\nTeapot Dome affair and Its nlmm-l\ncance in the coming election, He\ndeclared that the democrats ware\nattempting to find \u201can lssue in a tear\nw'-\u201c\n\u201cI'm proud to be the member of\nparty that can be hurt by a scandal,\"\nhe declared a few moments after\nmentioning the differnoce between\n\u201cunsecured loans and unearned\nfees.''\nIn eommenting upon the action of\nthe different government officlals in.\nvolved in the inveatigation, he sald:\nmentioning the differenca hetween\nprivate work and government werk.\nIn private work you get fired when\nyou do nething but In government\nwork they only fire you when you\ndo something.\"\nGov. Bhaw eulogized Linceln by\nusing a speech that Lincoln made\nabout Washington and by substitut.\ning Lincoln's name for that of the\nfirst president.\nFollowing this he took up the mat.\nter of economy In the present admin.\nistration, stressing the fact that be.\ncause of these economios $300,000,000\nhas been slashed from the war debt.\nThomas N. Swale, president of the\nolub, welcomed the guests to the\nbanquet and introduced the toast.\nmaster of the evening, Mayor John\nA. Kellogg, of Balllngham.\nKellogg's remark that he under.\nstood that Seattle might wake up\nthis election and elect a republican\nfor mayor brought the Liggest ap.\nplayse of the evening.\nGovernor Hart, In a brief speech,\ntold the gathering that his invita.\ntion to speak at the banquet re\nferred to him ax the \u201cretiring gov\nernor.\"\nHART DECLARES\nHE IS THRU\n\u201cIn spite of all rumors to the\ncentrary, I'm i, he declared. \u201cIn\nMissourl, where coma from,\"\u201d he\ncontinued, \u201cthere wns an old say.\ning that I'm following In retiring.\nIt was \u201cEnough of anything Is too\nmuch.\"\nHart threw down the gauntlet to\nopponents of the Administrative\ncode and quoted figures to show the\ngreat savings which he declares the\ncode has made.,\nLieut, Gdv. W, J. Coyle also made\nbyief speech and the usual tele\ngrams from national republican\nleaders to the club were read. Musie\nand the unvelling by President Sus.\nzallo of the University of Washing.\nton of a bust of Gov, Hart were\nother features of the program.\nMore than \u00a7OO persons were at\nthe banquet and later this number\nwas Increased to close to 1,000, it\nwas estimated,\nI\nLauds Lincoln as\n\nIndividual Winner\nAbraham Lincoln's greatness mn\u2018\nbe ascribed to the fuct that he was\nan individual conqueror, tha Rev.\nBky Wheeler told the Lions' club at\nthe Masonic club rooms Monday, Tho'\nmeeting was held in honor of the fa.\nmous American's birthday. \u201cLincoln\nsurmounted almest every concelvable\nhandicap,\u201d the speaker said. 1\nForeing entrance to the ponomca(\nat Thomas by breaking window of\nthe store bullding in which it is\nhoused, cracksmen blew the safe\nearly Monday and escaped with $53\nin stamps and \u00a75 In cash.\nRELIEF FOR FARMERS\nAT LAST! THEY ARE\nCLASSIFYING BOLTS\nWAHIIIN(I\u2018I\u2018\\\u2018)N. Yeb. 12.--Re-\nWef for the farmer at last?\nWhile legislators wrangle over\nfarm panaceas, the depariment of\ncommerce has taken definite ao\ntion, i\nIt has called a conference here\non February 10 to discuss stand.\nardizgation of nuts and bolts used\non farm implements and ma.\nchinery,\n*To help tha farmer,' It says,\n9ty\nAdvertising and\nNews Are Debated\n\u201cThe Mcln!lom}nlp Botween the\nNowspapor and the Advertising\nAgency\u201d was tha general subjeot\ndiscussed at the monthly meeting of\nthe King Kitsap group of the Wash.\nington Press assoclation Monday\nnight In the L. C. Smith Bullding\nrestaurant,\nThe speakers included Oren J.\nDavias, of the Journal of Commerce;\nF. W, Htrang, of the SHtrang\nProsser Advertising Agency; H. O\nStone, of the Izsard Advertising Co.:\nF. R. Singleton, of the Altnow.Sin.\ngleton Advertising Agency; Fred W.\nKennody, state manager of the\nPresa association, and Harry Laesile,\nof the Auburn Globe Republican,\neeet A ee S M\nOpportunity for Ownership\nPrinting was Invented in the first\nhalf of the fiftaenth century. Few\nooks were to be had even after that\ntime, other than in manuscript. Ow.\ning to fta bulk it was very difficult\nto seoure a copy of the Hible. To own\none meant an enormous outlay for\nthat period. Bo the masses of the\npeople were obliged to rent a manu\nsoript and pay for it by the hour. It\nis =ald that a load of hay waa the\nprice for rental for one hour a day,\nand that it was not so easy to get the\none hour, FPeopls then, as now, were\nhour, People then, as now, were\neager to read the SBeriptures, but to\ndo so they had to make many sacri\nfioes. Many have pald for It by im\nprisonment and some with their lives,\nBy contrast, what opportunities we\nhave today. There Is no restriction\non reading, the world is full of books,\nand the very best and greatest of\nthem is within immediate reach of\nevorybody who reads this per.\nWhether we approach It domm'. or\nwhether we desire i ns A specimen\nof the finest literature, almost for\nthe asking we can own one of the\nbest editions of the Bible ever print.\nod. For three coupons cut from this\npaper daily, and a very small sum\nthe Big Print Red Letter Hible is\nyours, Sse another column for offer.\no\n\niy\no 4 p wo\ni a\n|A t\ng\